1
00:00:00,588 --> 00:00:27,608
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:28,161 --> 00:00:32,707
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:35,289 --> 00:00:54,591
So yesterday evening we went through the various techniques and reminded ourselves that there's nothing mystical about these techniques, they're just skillful means, that's how they're referred to, upaya, skillful means to bring ourselves into the present moment.

4
00:00:56,561 --> 00:00:58,825
And just like all skills, you've got to work at them.

5
00:01:00,466 --> 00:01:03,752
And slowly they work for you, is the point, isn't it?

6
00:01:03,771 --> 00:01:09,799
They start working for you, slowing down, getting in the habit of just noting.

7
00:01:13,546 --> 00:01:24,561
These two especially are really quite powerful in terms of centering that attention on what it is you're actually experiencing in this present moment.

8
00:01:29,046 --> 00:01:32,692
So tonight we can have a look at these hindrances.

9
00:01:33,212 --> 00:01:35,075
That's the Buddha's word for them.

10
00:01:36,237 --> 00:01:43,207
They're more hindrances in the sense of stopping us from concentration.

11
00:01:43,227 --> 00:01:48,436
They drag us away from the moment because that's what they do, that's their job.

12
00:01:48,736 --> 00:01:51,561
Their job is to keep us occupied on something else.

13
00:01:54,950 --> 00:02:22,358
but when we doing vipassana as such then we can see them really as ways to get to know ourselves and it's often the case that when we begin to meditate we get in touch with emotions that we might not have fully accepted about ourselves before you know often our family history has forbidden us to feel things you know

14
00:02:26,793 --> 00:02:50,995
crying being angry being jealous all these things in your family history depending on the situation there have taught you to sort of push things away not to really look at them and but unfortunately of course they remain at that subliminal level and affect our actions you know it puts a puts a pressure on what we're doing

15
00:02:53,117 --> 00:03:04,174
So, for instance, in jealousy, if we're jealous of somebody, but we've never looked at it, and we've pushed it away, and we've felt this sort of subliminal guilt about that, we might be over-praising.

16
00:03:05,336 --> 00:03:06,877
We compensate for it.

17
00:03:06,897 --> 00:03:10,483
All these things, I think, were very well understood by Freud, actually.

18
00:03:12,004 --> 00:03:14,568
He captured all that very well.

19
00:03:16,473 --> 00:03:45,652
so one of the things about our meditation is really to open up to ourselves and to receive whatever is whatever we have been suppressing often when you come to Eastern teachers in fact I've just received an email if you ever work with Eastern teachers they they tend to push effort and concentration and this often

20
00:03:47,016 --> 00:04:16,973
means that the meditator ends up suppressing stuff in this particular email that I've just received the instructions from the Burmese teacher was if an emotion comes you note it like anger or happiness and then you immediately go back to the breath and the aim of that really is to center the whole attention on the three characteristics but especially

21
00:04:17,947 --> 00:04:46,588
the idea of impermanence and in this way a person can be pushed towards some sort of deep insight but it's at the expense really of not purifying the heart and in the Buddha's teaching the purification of the heart has to go hand in hand with insight you can't leapfrog into liberation

22
00:04:47,598 --> 00:04:50,043
There has to be a complete clearance of the heart.

23
00:04:54,290 --> 00:04:57,295
We say the path is sila-samadhi-panya.

24
00:04:57,355 --> 00:05:01,923
Sila is your conduct, is your behavior.

25
00:05:03,206 --> 00:05:09,858
And this manifests your attitude, this manifests your virtue or lack of it.

26
00:05:10,716 --> 00:05:16,586
The samādhi is the training of the mind to be still, which is just part and parcel of the vipassana process.

27
00:05:16,966 --> 00:05:18,910
And the paññā is the insight which liberates.

28
00:05:20,994 --> 00:05:28,887
So, whether we like it or not, we have to go to hell before we get to heaven.

29
00:05:29,307 --> 00:05:31,451
It's just one of those things.

30
00:05:31,531 --> 00:05:34,596
There has to be a process of purification.

31
00:05:34,615 --> 00:05:36,319
And what we discover is,

32
00:05:36,889 --> 00:05:42,137
that the only way to purify the heart is to let it speak, is to let it manifest its feelings.

33
00:05:45,360 --> 00:05:48,584
And that's painful for us, we don't like doing that.

34
00:05:48,605 --> 00:05:56,896
It's hard to be with, you know, depression, anger, the whole gamut of human suffering, which everybody has to some degree or other, I think.

35
00:06:00,779 --> 00:06:04,365
So when the Buddha delineated these

36
00:06:04,935 --> 00:06:33,963
emotional attitudinal states he just called them the hindrances and the first one not surprisingly had all those things to do with desire and looking at the process of desire we find that when something comes up that we like that we want you see when we like it we want it very simple isn't it you like it so you want it

37
00:06:34,399 --> 00:06:36,521
You see that in little children, don't you?

38
00:06:37,463 --> 00:06:40,086
When they see something like a toy, they want it.

39
00:06:40,107 --> 00:06:42,389
It's quite natural, isn't it?

40
00:06:42,408 --> 00:06:46,754
So that never leaves us, the wanting because, you know, liking something.

41
00:06:46,915 --> 00:06:47,935
Now why do we do that?

42
00:06:48,516 --> 00:06:50,499
It's because when we get what we want, we're happy.

43
00:06:51,800 --> 00:06:52,641
It makes us feel happy.

44
00:06:52,661 --> 00:06:55,163
It gives us a certain gratification.

45
00:06:57,887 --> 00:07:04,254
And what happens is then that there's an underlying belief, you see, that

46
00:07:04,757 --> 00:07:07,201
If only you can get what you want, you'll always be happy.

47
00:07:09,663 --> 00:07:12,848
And you're into the great consumerist society.

48
00:07:14,009 --> 00:07:18,694
And of course adverts play on that to the nth degree, don't they?

49
00:07:18,714 --> 00:07:20,237
And they stick desires together.

50
00:07:20,276 --> 00:07:25,684
So you always get these beautiful men and women standing next to the car you want.

51
00:07:27,245 --> 00:07:32,992
The suggestion of erotic and romantic happiness which goes with a Jaguar.

52
00:07:35,976 --> 00:07:42,625
So these desires that we have are not just simple, you know, I want to something.

53
00:07:42,665 --> 00:07:48,012
They're part of a root theology.

54
00:07:48,411 --> 00:07:51,175
They're part of a way that we look at life.

55
00:07:51,615 --> 00:07:53,899
It's our relationship to our lives.

56
00:07:54,600 --> 00:07:55,701
Happiness, for heaven's sake.

57
00:07:55,721 --> 00:07:58,125
I mean, what do you want if it's not happiness?

58
00:07:58,545 --> 00:08:00,067
You know, if you ask somebody, what do you want to be?

59
00:08:00,086 --> 00:08:02,170
They want to be happy.

60
00:08:02,189 --> 00:08:03,350
And they'll define that.

61
00:08:04,040 --> 00:08:07,223
you know, good job, nice relationship, etc., etc., a big list of things.

62
00:08:07,524 --> 00:08:09,747
But basically, everybody wants to be happy.

63
00:08:11,790 --> 00:08:24,107
And the mistake, the great mistake, is to believe that the world, the sensual world, which is all we experience, is what can deliver that happiness.

64
00:08:27,225 --> 00:08:55,123
as far as the world exists out there is in a sense irrelevant it's how we experience it which is relevant and it comes through our senses therefore we live in a sensual world from the inner point of view and when the senses deliver those very pleasant feelings pleasant states of mind then we're happy and the confusion of course

65
00:08:55,340 --> 00:09:01,807
lies in the fact that happiness is an emotional state.

66
00:09:01,827 --> 00:09:05,893
So therefore we're always chasing the next emotional state, the next high.

67
00:09:07,534 --> 00:09:10,739
And in our society that's become a disease, hasn't it?

68
00:09:12,260 --> 00:09:14,724
It leads to compulsive action, addiction.

69
00:09:16,245 --> 00:09:18,568
The whole of life is about what are you going to do this Saturday?

70
00:09:18,589 --> 00:09:19,669
Where are you going to do this Sunday?

71
00:09:19,690 --> 00:09:20,831
Where are you going to go for your holiday?

72
00:09:21,793 --> 00:09:22,714
Have you seen this film?

73
00:09:23,385 --> 00:09:28,692
If you read that book, it's always, what's the next thing which is going to bring me this little high?

74
00:09:33,197 --> 00:09:36,600
And the downside of that, of course, is when there isn't one.

75
00:09:38,102 --> 00:09:49,515
So because we like living on these little highs, on these, you know, like what's the next thing to be done, and they're not there, there's that disappointment, there's a sense of loss, a grief.

76
00:09:50,878 --> 00:09:51,739
Like, what am I going to do?

77
00:09:58,451 --> 00:10:18,496
Worse than that, because of the inbuilt obsolescence of these pleasures, the fact that they can't maintain that same buzz that you got the first time, they lead to an easy boredom.

78
00:10:18,517 --> 00:10:28,188
I read this article where this woman described the first go at crack, as she called it, riding the dragon.

79
00:10:29,570 --> 00:10:36,577
And then she said, after that, you're always chasing that primary experience, but you never get it.

80
00:10:38,581 --> 00:10:40,043
And that's the problem with addiction.

81
00:10:40,403 --> 00:10:45,109
You're always trying to get the primary wow experience you had.

82
00:10:46,009 --> 00:10:57,163
And of course, when it comes to things like drugs and whatnot, the body becomes immune to it, it becomes hardened to it, it finds a way of absorbing the shock.

83
00:10:58,644 --> 00:11:27,740
and when a person comes off drugs they often they sometimes forget how resistant the body was to the drug they were taking and often when they slip back into the old habit for one reason or another they could be rejoicing they kill themselves they overdose now in a little way in a less dramatic way that's what we're doing all the time

84
00:11:30,082 --> 00:11:37,533
All the time we're seeking happiness in sensual pleasure and we're getting to a point where we're bored.

85
00:11:38,836 --> 00:11:40,958
So boredom says, seek, seek more pleasure.

86
00:11:41,259 --> 00:11:42,782
Variety is the spice of life.

87
00:11:42,841 --> 00:11:43,302
Off you go.

88
00:11:44,884 --> 00:11:47,148
And there's incessant search.

89
00:11:47,168 --> 00:11:48,330
We don't want to feel boredom.

90
00:11:48,350 --> 00:11:51,534
Boredom is not a very pleasant state to be in.

91
00:11:56,846 --> 00:12:00,510
And if it gets too much, if it gets really bored, you lose the purpose of living.

92
00:12:00,591 --> 00:12:02,011
It moves towards despair.

93
00:12:05,576 --> 00:12:06,998
It can be on a professional level.

94
00:12:07,677 --> 00:12:13,344
If your work has always been very interesting and it disappears, what are you left with?

95
00:12:13,364 --> 00:12:15,907
You're left with this hole, aren't you?

96
00:12:15,927 --> 00:12:16,847
What are you going to do now?

97
00:12:18,129 --> 00:12:25,437
Because you can't gain that same intensity of experience, life becomes boring, becomes empty, meaningless.

98
00:12:27,289 --> 00:12:36,640
And it's only because we've defined life as being something which is exciting, something which is always going to deliver this very pleasant state.

99
00:12:43,849 --> 00:12:49,075
So there's a real heavy consequence from indulgence.

100
00:12:52,078 --> 00:12:54,140
It's the...

101
00:12:55,201 --> 00:12:59,486
Indulgence here, by the way, is referring to all types of attachments.

102
00:13:00,729 --> 00:13:04,754
So we're not just talking about missing your tea in the morning.

103
00:13:04,774 --> 00:13:07,719
I mean, that's pretty disastrous.

104
00:13:07,739 --> 00:13:19,995
But we talk about heavy stuff like the loss of your job if you enjoyed your work, the loss of a relationship, the death of somebody close.

105
00:13:20,297 --> 00:13:24,802
All these are very extraordinarily painful experiences for us.

106
00:13:26,486 --> 00:13:30,110
And the pain is the measure of the attachment.

107
00:13:30,130 --> 00:13:31,631
Pain is the measure of the attachment.

108
00:13:33,934 --> 00:13:38,219
So when somebody dies, for instance, there's this, we call it grief.

109
00:13:39,259 --> 00:13:41,763
But it's like a huge sore, isn't it, in your heart.

110
00:13:42,583 --> 00:13:46,368
It's extraordinarily painful and a real lack.

111
00:13:46,388 --> 00:13:49,610
And we like to think of it as our love.

112
00:13:50,412 --> 00:13:52,533
You know, this is how much I really love the person.

113
00:13:52,573 --> 00:13:53,575
I miss them so much.

114
00:13:55,376 --> 00:14:00,042
That's the confusion, you see, because we've confused love with this attachment.

115
00:14:00,062 --> 00:14:01,764
But the grief is the measure of attachment.

116
00:14:03,606 --> 00:14:12,216
And if we don't see that, then the grief becomes chronic, because every time the grief begins to lessen, you think you're losing the love of the person.

117
00:14:12,976 --> 00:14:16,321
You've got to re-grieve to make sure you're still really loving them.

118
00:14:18,644 --> 00:14:21,267
And it's only when you begin to realize that grief

119
00:14:21,517 --> 00:14:45,751
in this sense grief of loss is actually a measure of attachment that you can let it go and you begin to realize that love is something of a higher nature love allows things to be if it was the time for the person to die one is easy with it you don't indulge in the grief

120
00:14:46,508 --> 00:14:49,513
you see it as something which is unwholesome.

121
00:14:50,092 --> 00:14:52,197
It's a product of that attachment.

122
00:14:56,763 --> 00:15:11,225
At a lesser level, you see, objects that we own, you know, like, it could be something quite costly, like a car, or a computer, a laptop, or something that's not so costly, like your mobile.

123
00:15:12,326 --> 00:15:13,207
Somebody thieves it.

124
00:15:14,857 --> 00:15:16,159
You feel angry about it.

125
00:15:17,042 --> 00:15:18,364
You know, bloody thief.

126
00:15:19,905 --> 00:15:21,769
And there might be some grief.

127
00:15:22,350 --> 00:15:24,573
And you go around saying, you know, do you know what?

128
00:15:24,614 --> 00:15:26,898
Somebody stole my phone, my mobile.

129
00:15:28,860 --> 00:15:29,942
It isn't your mobile anymore.

130
00:15:31,083 --> 00:15:31,826
It belongs to the thief.

131
00:15:31,966 --> 00:15:32,667
They're using it.

132
00:15:33,187 --> 00:15:36,072
They're the ones who have the mobile.

133
00:15:36,653 --> 00:15:40,038
But there's still this figment in the imagination that it's still mine.

134
00:15:43,106 --> 00:15:44,869
which is a social construct, isn't it?

135
00:15:44,969 --> 00:15:50,433
It's a legal arrangement that we've come with each other, that if I say this is mine, it belongs to me.

136
00:15:50,953 --> 00:16:02,664
And there's somehow a feeling that it belongs to me in a deep, like it's attached to me in a sort of visceral, emotional way.

137
00:16:04,206 --> 00:16:10,532
Whereas when we look at something like a clock or something, or a mobile, actually all you can do with objects is use them.

138
00:16:11,557 --> 00:16:15,183
To own them is a painful thing, emotionally I mean.

139
00:16:15,784 --> 00:16:18,269
We might legally own it, fine, that's not a problem.

140
00:16:22,195 --> 00:16:30,908
I mean if you own something which you actually want to get rid of and you get compensation if somebody does thieve it, you leave it in obvious places.

141
00:16:32,731 --> 00:16:33,533
That's not a problem.

142
00:16:37,124 --> 00:16:47,759
Put your four and a half year old computer, which is guaranteed for five years, you know, and leave it out in the park somewhere.

143
00:16:50,624 --> 00:16:53,347
Oh, fiddle these poor companies.

144
00:16:59,677 --> 00:17:05,645
So, one of the first things is to begin to see that psychology within ourselves.

145
00:17:06,200 --> 00:17:16,192
That's why I'm so intent on this business of eating and, you know, when we drink something, because right there we can see it, you see, right there.

146
00:17:20,057 --> 00:17:24,982
I mean, supposing tomorrow, for instance, when it came to five o'clock, you said to yourself, well, I won't have any tea.

147
00:17:25,242 --> 00:17:26,163
I won't even have the whiskey.

148
00:17:28,086 --> 00:17:30,789
I'll have a cup of cold water and I'll sit here and watch the pain.

149
00:17:34,059 --> 00:18:03,257
and what we're watching is the attachment now the great thing about these attachments is that once you stop indulging them they actually do die away there's a whole process there of deconditioning and very quickly you become accustomed to a new order once you've set your heart to it so here for instance you know you've come into a very strange sort of regime you know you get up at 3.30

150
00:18:05,853 --> 00:18:08,277
breakfast, lunch, sit here, walk.

151
00:18:08,778 --> 00:18:10,160
Crazy, really, when you think about it.

152
00:18:10,621 --> 00:18:16,270
If you describe it to a person who knows nothing about meditation, they think, well, they must be a bit off.

153
00:18:18,534 --> 00:18:19,194
Must have gone off.

154
00:18:22,381 --> 00:18:27,249
But I think you'll see that even within three or four days, you just get up, you just do it.

155
00:18:27,469 --> 00:18:29,633
You just re-habituate it to something.

156
00:18:31,250 --> 00:18:41,325
And really that's the trick when it comes to habits that we find difficult for ourselves is to know that actually all you have to do is go through the pain of detoxing.

157
00:18:44,589 --> 00:18:50,898
And replace it of course with something which is more wholesome.

158
00:18:50,919 --> 00:18:56,185
Because unfortunately we have time, we keep moving from one moment to the next.

159
00:18:56,507 --> 00:18:57,949
You've got to fill it up with something.

160
00:18:58,502 --> 00:19:05,211
And if you can find something more skillful than what you were doing, then of course that is going to have a psychological effect.

161
00:19:05,250 --> 00:19:06,993
It's going to create a certain contentment.

162
00:19:09,616 --> 00:19:13,080
And contentment is a big word in the spiritual world.

163
00:19:13,902 --> 00:19:17,006
Contentment is the mind without desire.

164
00:19:18,708 --> 00:19:19,789
The mind without desire.

165
00:19:21,551 --> 00:19:25,375
When we say desire here, remember, we're translating this one word, tanha.

166
00:19:25,936 --> 00:19:28,240
There is another word in Pali, chanda.

167
00:19:28,928 --> 00:19:34,317
which can be either wrong or right, can be a good desire or a bad desire.

168
00:19:35,057 --> 00:19:39,144
So that if we want to sit, that's a good desire, and we should reinforce it.

169
00:19:39,786 --> 00:19:55,392
The desire that we're talking about in terms of what causes problems is the desire whereby we believe that something sensual, something of this world, this phenomenal world, is going to deliver perfect happiness.

170
00:19:57,852 --> 00:20:01,317
So when we're eating, you see, we're trying to make that distinction.

171
00:20:01,738 --> 00:20:08,207
So we're not seeking happiness in food, but we find that when we eat food, a certain appreciative joy arises.

172
00:20:09,328 --> 00:20:10,891
And that's natural to that process.

173
00:20:12,373 --> 00:20:19,242
It's natural for the body to feel good when you feed it something, and it's natural for the mind to resonate that goodness.

174
00:20:23,107 --> 00:20:26,272
Even at a level, should we say, of...

175
00:20:27,468 --> 00:20:37,462
Just relationships, there's a case where the Buddha is asked, when people listen to your dharma and they don't receive it, they walk away from it, how do you feel?

176
00:20:37,624 --> 00:20:40,448
He says, fine, I don't feel unhappy or anything.

177
00:20:41,088 --> 00:20:44,934
And the reason for that is this understanding of karma.

178
00:20:45,134 --> 00:20:47,538
The person isn't ready to move that way.

179
00:20:48,400 --> 00:20:51,565
And it's no skin off his nose, is it?

180
00:20:51,846 --> 00:20:54,690
The Buddha's all right.

181
00:20:54,670 --> 00:21:18,990
got his food and he's under a tree and he's happy as though his personal happiness is dependent on somebody believing or following his instructions or not but when somebody but he says when somebody actually accepts the teaching and begins to train he's filled with joy and that's that sympathetic resonance

182
00:21:22,902 --> 00:21:30,530
I think some people think that when the Buddha was liberated, he sort of turned into this hardened blob.

183
00:21:32,393 --> 00:21:34,115
He no longer related to the world.

184
00:21:34,174 --> 00:21:42,163
He sort of walked around as a sort of automaton who spoke the Dharma and didn't have a sort of emotional life.

185
00:21:43,005 --> 00:21:44,646
But it's quite plain that he did.

186
00:21:45,186 --> 00:21:46,288
He was quite charismatic.

187
00:21:46,929 --> 00:21:51,795
And we talk about the four illimitables, which we can go into more detail towards the end of the week.

188
00:21:53,394 --> 00:22:13,647
in a sense all beautiful emotions beautiful mental states are illimitable but the four of them as it were captures a great deal of them love, compassion, joy and peace so it's not as though

189
00:22:14,336 --> 00:22:16,701
you know, we're trying to get rid of the joy of life.

190
00:22:16,741 --> 00:22:29,510
It's very important to grasp that, because if we make that mistake, if we make the mistake of thinking that it's the body which is the problem, if I didn't eat, then I wouldn't get attached.

191
00:22:30,537 --> 00:22:40,869
That's the mistake of the self-mortifier, of the great ascetic who looks like a famine victim.

192
00:22:40,890 --> 00:22:45,035
They don't eat, they don't go anywhere near something that's lovely or beautiful.

193
00:22:48,799 --> 00:22:58,451
Again, the Buddha, you see, when he is on alms round, he comes away, he's got his food, and he's with Ananda, his attendant, and he says to Ananda, let's go

194
00:22:59,005 --> 00:23:28,152
to this shrine to this beautiful shrine and eat our food why doesn't he eat just down there on the side of the road in the dust or find a donkey and be a real ascetic he doesn't he wants to go somewhere beautiful when he he goes off to meditate by himself into the forest you know leaves leaves the crowds and they say to him why do you do that now that you're full liberated

195
00:23:30,021 --> 00:23:36,394
And he says, I do it for my own quiet abiding, and for the benefit of others, as a good example to others.

196
00:23:37,056 --> 00:23:39,500
But you notice, it's the quiet abiding that comes first.

197
00:23:40,843 --> 00:23:44,048
